ster, Leominster, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Leominster, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bridstow, Ross on Wye, Herefordshire, England":"Bridstow, Herefordshire, England","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1550–1610":"1550–1610","1580–Male":"1580–Deceased","1582–1603":"1582–1603","1530–1550":"1530–1550","1538–1614":"1538–1614","about 1580":"about 1580","1 August 1603":"1 August 1603","1550":"1550","1582":"1582","1571":"1571","1580":"1580","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1538":"1538","1614":"1614","1603":"1603","England":"England, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Abbots Langley, Hertfordshire, England":"Abbots Langley, Hertfordshire, England","Leominster, Herefordshire,England":"England, United Kingdom","Leominster, Leominster, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Leominster, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bridstow, Ross on Wye, Herefordshire, England":"Bridstow, Herefordshire, England","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Meals","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of <b>Meale</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. One origin of <b>Meale</b> is as a nickname from Middle English <i>mele</i> ‘meal, ground cereal’, perhaps for a maker or seller of meal. Compare   Millman  .","variant of <b>Meale</b> with plural <i>-s</i>. An alternative origin of <b>Meale</b> is as a topographic name from Middle English <i>mele</i> ‘sand-hill’ (Old Norse <i>melr</i>), as found in such placenames as North Meols, Ravensmeols (both Lancashire), and Great Meols (Cheshire).","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Millman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Isadore, Golda, Iren.","English: occupational name for a worker at a mill, from Middle English <i>mille</i>, <i>milne</i> ‘mill’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>mele</i> ‘meal, ground cereal’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, presumably either a grinder or vendor of meal."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Christopher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":8,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":19,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":21,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":35,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":37,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":50,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Christopher Meals was born in 1550, in Bridstow, Herefordshire, England, his father, Meals, was 20 and his mother, Elina Julian Meols, was 13. He married Elizabeth Webb in 1580, in Leominster, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1610, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1550–1610":"1550–1610","1580–Male":"1580–Surnud","1582–1603":"1582–1603","1530–1550":"1530–1550","1538–1614":"1538–1614","about 1580":"umbes 1580","1 August 1603":"1. august 1603","1550":"1550","1582":"1582","1571":"1571","1580":